   void PropWriteMethodology(const int handle)
   {
      FileWriteString(handle,
         "<div class=\"section\">\n<h2>Methodology &mdash; How Scores Are Calculated</h2>\n<div class=\"method\">\n");
      FileWriteString(handle,
         "<div class=\"m-item\">\n<h3>Pass Rate (All-Time)</h3>\n" +
         "<p>Passed runs &divide; total starts for the strategy, shown as a percentage. A run <b>passes</b> when equity reaches the profit target (" + DoubleToString(PropProfitTargetPercent, 1) + "% of starting balance) before any rule breach. A run <b>blows</b> when total drawdown exceeds " + DoubleToString(PropMaxTotalDrawdownPercent, 1) + "% or daily drawdown exceeds " + DoubleToString(PropDailyDrawdownPercent, 1) + "%.</p>\n" +
         "<p><b>Caution:</b> Pass rate rewards strategies that hit the profit target <i>quickly</i>. A fast strategy resolves runs as &ldquo;passed&rdquo; before it ever has time to blow, inflating its pass rate. Slower-but-safer strategies accumulate &ldquo;active&rdquo; (unresolved) runs that drag their pass rate down without indicating any real risk. Use <b>True Blow Risk</b> and <b>Safety Score</b> below to judge actual danger.</p>\n</div>\n");
      FileWriteString(handle,
         "<div class=\"m-item\">\n<h3>True Blow Risk</h3>\n" +
         "<p>Blown runs &divide; (passed + blown runs), shown as a percentage. This <b>excludes active (unresolved) runs entirely</b>, so it answers: <i>of the runs that actually finished one way or the other, what fraction blew?</i></p>\n" +
         "<p>Unlike pass rate, this is not distorted by speed. A strategy with 0% blow risk has <b>never</b> blown a single account among all resolved runs &mdash; the safest possible record. Lower is better. A strategy with 80% pass rate and 5% blow risk is far safer than one with 83% pass rate and 13% blow risk, even though the report sorts them in the opposite order by pass rate alone.</p>\n</div>\n");
      FileWriteString(handle,
         "<div class=\"m-item\">\n<h3>Safety Score</h3>\n" +
         "<p>100 &minus; True Blow Risk. Higher is safer. A score of 100 means the strategy has never blown an account (0% blow risk). A score of 85 means 15% of resolved runs blew. This is the single most reliable column for ranking by <b>risk of failure</b> rather than speed of success.</p>\n" +
         "<p><b>How to read it:</b> Sort by this column (click the header) to find the strategies least likely to breach propfirm drawdown rules. Pair high-safety strategies with high-recency strategies to get both durability and current-regime fit.</p>\n</div>\n");
      if(PropRecencyHalfLifeDays > 0.0)
      {
         FileWriteString(handle,
            "<div class=\"m-item\">\n<h3>Recency Score</h3>\n" +
            "<p>Exponential time-weighted pass rate. Each run is weighted by <code>w = exp(-&lambda;&middot;age)</code>, where <i>age</i> is days since the run started and <code>&lambda; = ln(2) / " + DoubleToString(PropRecencyHalfLifeDays, 1) + "</code> (the half-life in days). Older runs contribute exponentially less. Score = &Sigma;(passed&middot;w) &divide; &Sigma;(all&middot;w). The ranking uses this score when recency is enabled.</p>\n</div>\n");
      }
      FileWriteString(handle,
         "<div class=\"m-item\">\n<h3>Trend (sparkline)</h3>\n" +
         "<p>Per-day cumulative net = &Sigma;(passes &minus; breaches) up to that day. Each strategy is ranked daily by that day's pass rate; the sparkline plots the running cumulative net &mdash; <span style=\"color:#16a34a\">green</span> = net positive, <span style=\"color:#dc2626\">red</span> = net negative. Hover for the daily breakdown.</p>\n</div>\n");
      FileWriteString(handle,
         "<div class=\"m-item\">\n<h3>Persistence Score (0&ndash;100)</h3>\n" +
         "<p>A composite of how consistently a strategy stays near the top of the daily ranking. It is a weighted blend of four sub-metrics (shown in the five green-tinted columns):</p>\n" +
         "<ul>\n" +
         "<li><b>Top10% (weight 40%)</b> &mdash; share of ranked days the strategy placed in the top 10.</li>\n" +
         "<li><b>Avg Rank (weight 25%)</b> &mdash; mean daily rank normalized to 0&ndash;100 (higher is better): (N &minus; avgRank) / (N &minus; 1) &times; 100.</li>\n" +
         "<li><b>Stability (weight 20%)</b> &mdash; 100 minus rank volatility, where volatility = mean absolute day-to-day rank change normalized by the number of ranked strategies.</li>\n" +
         "<li><b>Momentum (weight 15%)</b> &mdash; compares the average rank of the recent half of days to the earlier half. 50 = no change, &gt;50 = improving, &lt;50 = declining.</li>\n" +
         "</ul>\n</div>\n");
      FileWriteString(handle,
         "<div class=\"m-item\">\n<h3>Profit Factor (PF)</h3>\n" +
         "<p>Gross profit &divide; |gross loss| across all runs of the strategy. PF &ge; 1 indicates net profitable trading.</p>\n</div>\n");
      FileWriteString(handle,
         "<div class=\"m-item\">\n<h3>Avg R:R (Reward : Risk)</h3>\n" +
         "<p>Average win ($) &divide; average loss ($) per strategy, where each trade exits at the Virtual Take Profit / Stop Loss money thresholds.</p>\n</div>\n");
      FileWriteString(handle,
         "<div class=\"m-item\">\n<h3>Net P/L (Avg / Best / Worst)</h3>\n" +
         "<p>End balance &minus; starting balance. <b>Avg Net</b> is the mean across runs; <b>Best</b> and <b>Worst Net</b> are the single most and least profitable runs for the strategy.</p>\n</div>\n");
      FileWriteString(handle,
         "<div class=\"m-item\">\n<h3>Ranking / Sort Order</h3>\n" +
         "<p>Strategies are sorted by <b>recency score</b> when enabled (then all-time pass rate, then average net P/L as tiebreakers); otherwise by all-time pass rate then average net P/L. Click any column header to re-sort the table.</p>\n</div>\n");
      FileWriteString(handle, "</div>\n</div>\n");
   }

